{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 22:41:18.734052", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos (fat‑tree) EBGP fabric\n\nSummary (high level)\n- Data plane: Hosts are reachable across the fabric. The automated reachability check shows successful pings between hosts (0% loss reported for all tested pairs).\n- Control plane: BGP routes for all /24 host subnets are present in routing tables on routers (many BGP-learned prefixes visible).\n- Configuration anomaly (critical): Multiple routers have BGP neighbor statements that reference the local interface address (the router’s own link address) instead of the remote peer’s address. Router‑IDs on some devices are also inconsistent with expected local addresses. This is systemic: present on leaf→spine and spine→super‑spine links.\n- Likely root cause: a template/automation error that populated neighbor IPs (and some router‑IDs) with the local interface addresses instead of the remote peer addresses (an “off‑by‑one” / swapped‑side mapping when generating configs).\n- Impact: At time of observation the data plane and BGP forwarding appear functional (routes are present and hosts can communicate). However the control-plane configuration inconsistencies create a fragile state that could lead to session failures after reboots/config reloads or make troubleshooting harder.\n\nEvidence and findings (detailed)\n\n1) Data plane (reachability)\n- get_reachability results: all tested host-to-host pings show status \"ok\" and 0% loss. Example: pc_0_0 -> pc_0_2: loss_percent 0.0, rtt_avg 7.883 ms. No packet loss observed in the provided reachability sample.\n\n2) Control plane (routes present)\n- On leaf_router_0_0 (show ip route excerpt) many remote /24s are installed as BGP routes. Example:\n  - B>* 10.0.1.0/24 [20/0] via 172.16.1.48, eth3, ...\n  - B>* 10.2.0.0/24 [20/0] via 172.16.1.0, eth0, ...\n  This indicates BGP route propagation is happening and forwarding entries are populated.\n\n3) Configuration anomalies (explicit examples)\n- leaf_router_0_0 (running-config):\n  - bgp router-id 172.16.1.1\n  - neighbor 172.16.1.0 remote-as 65100\n  - neighbor 172.16.1.16 remote-as 65101\n  - neighbor 172.16.1.32 remote-as 65102\n  - ... (neighbors continue with .48, .64, .80, .96, .112)\n- leaf_router_0_0 (route table / connected IPs):\n  - C>* 172.16.1.0/31 is directly connected, eth0\n  - C>* 172.16.1.16/31 is directly connected, eth1\n  - C>* 172.16.1.32/31 is directly connected, eth2\n  - ...\n  Diagnosis: neighbor statements on leaf_router_0_0 reference addresses that are the leaf’s own directly connected IPs (e.g., 172.16.1.0 is local), not the address of the remote spine peer on that /31. The router-id is set to 172.16.1.1 (which is not the leaf’s directly connected address in these C routes and appears to belong to the peer side), showing inconsistent/id swapped values.\n\n- leaf_router_0_1 (running-config):\n  - bgp router-id 172.16.1.3\n  - neighbor 172.16.1.2 remote-as 65100\n  - neighbor 172.16.1.18 remote-as 65101\n  - ...\n- leaf_router_0_1 (connected):\n  - C>* 172.16.1.2/31 is directly connected, eth0\n  - C>* 172.16.1.18/31 is directly connected, eth1\n  - ...\n  Same pattern: neighbor statements point to local addresses.\n\n- spine_router_0_0 (running-config):\n  - bgp router-id 172.16.0.1\n  - neighbor 172.16.0.0 remote-as 65000\n  - neighbor 172.16.0.64 remote-as 65000\n  - ...\n- spine_router_0_0 (connected):\n  - C>* 172.16.0.0/31 is directly connected, eth0\n  - C>* 172.16.0.2/31 is directly connected, eth1\n  - ...\n  Diagnosis: spine_router_0_0 neighbor toward the super‑spine is configured as 172.16.0.0 (the local interface IP) instead of the super‑spine’s adjacent address (.1). Similar local‑address neighbor entries appear across spine→super‑spine links.\n\n- super_spine_router_0 (running-config):\n  - bgp router-id 172.16.0.0\n  - neighbor 172.16.0.1 remote-as 65100\n  - neighbor 172.16.0.3 remote-as 65101\n  - ...\n  The super‑spine is configured with neighbor addresses that correspond to the spine’s peer addresses (e.g., .1, .3). This is the \"other side\" of the mismatch: super_spine appears to reference the remote side’s addresses, while the spine lists the local addresses as the neighbor.\n\n4) Pattern and scope\n- The same “neighbor = local interface IP” pattern is repeated:\n  - leaves list neighbors equal to their own 172.16.1.x interface addresses (should be the spine addresses).\n  - spines list neighbor addresses equal to their own 172.16.0.x interface addresses (should be super_spine addresses).\n- Router-IDs on leaves appear to be set to the expected spine addresses (e.g., leaf_router_0_0 router-id 172.16.1.1), inconsistent with that device's own connected addresses.\n\n5) Logical root cause (probable)\n- A systematic configuration or templating error assigned neighbor IPs (and some router-ids) with the local interface address rather than the remote peer address. In other words, the automation/template likely took the local side of each /31 when generating the \"neighbor <ip>\" statements, instead of the remote side. This is repeated across leaf/spine and spine/super‑spine levels, which strongly indicates a script/template bug rather than manual one-off typos.\n\n6) Observed impact and risk\n- Observed impact right now: none visible in the data plane — BGP routes exist and hosts can communicate (0% loss).\n- Risk: the control-plane is in a non‑idiomatic/fragile state. The asymmetry/inconsistency may cause:\n  - BGP neighbor sessions to be brittle (might break on restart or if any interface addresses change).\n  - Confusing behavior during troubleshooting (router-IDs and neighbor IPs do not match expected topology).\n  - Potential failures if any element is reconfigured or if configuration is reapplied by the same automation (it will reproduce the same wrong mapping).\n  - Difficulty scaling or integrating additional devices due to the template error being systemic.\n\nConclusions\n- Network forwarding (data plane) is currently healthy; hosts can reach each other and BGP routes are present.\n- There is a clear and systemic configuration anomaly: many BGP neighbor statements (and some router-ids) are using the local interface IP instead of the remote peer IP. The pattern is repeated across leaf and spine layers and between spines and the super-spine.\n- The most likely root cause is an automation/template error that swapped local/remote addresses when generating BGP neighbor entries (and in some router-id assignments).\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Enumerate all offending neighbor lines and match them to the corresponding connected interface addresses (complete list).\n- Query BGP neighbor session states (show bgp summary) on each router to confirm exactly which sessions are established and whether any are flapping.\n- Provide a concise checklist of the specific misconfigured neighbor statements per device (no remediation steps — just mapping and verification data).\n\n(Per your instruction I have not provided remediation steps. Tell me if you want the additional verification output described above.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 20264, "output_tokens": 5868, "total_tokens": 26132, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8832}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4096}}}
